"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91500","Home Office","false","2014-09-30","<p /> <p>Migration Statistics, part of Home Office Statistics, is responsible for producing the Quarterly Immigration Statistics and regularly reviews the <br>content. The inclusion of new datasets depends on several factors, including: availability of the data; data quality; public interest; work capacity of Migration Statistics.</p><p />","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-09-30T15:06:32.8077616Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91500/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91500/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-10","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will include in the Quarterly Immigration Statistics figures for the numbers of (a) Rule 35 applications, (b) detainees released automatically as a result of Rule 35 applications, (c) Rule 35 applications refused on exceptional grounds and (d) Rule 35 applications subsequently escalated through the Home Office Enforcement management claim, by immigration removal centre.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","208966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91501","Home Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>Border Force has a total of 19 body scanners for the purposes of detecting drugs and other illegal contraband at the border; all of which are operational. The average cost of each unit is approximately £133,500 and running revenue cost is £6.50 per unit over a 24hr period.<br><br>Border Force also has 5 Passive Millimetre Wave Imaging devices which scan vehicles for the presence of clandestines, all of which are operational. The average capital cost of each unit is approximately £800,000. The maintenance cost to the Home Office over a 24 hour period is approximately £83 per unit.<br><br>The Department for Transport requires Security (Body) Scanners to be deployed at some UK airports, at their cost, as part of the outbound air passenger screening process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","208971","2014-10-13T10:52:59.5396938Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91501/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91501/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-10","Borders: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the (a) capital and (b) revenue costs are of operating a body scanning machine at a single point of entry over a 24-hour period.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","208897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91502","Home Office","false","2014-09-24","<p>On 18 August 2014 the Prime Minister announced that the family test was being formalised as part of the impact assessment for all domestic policies. From October 2014, every new domestic policy will be examined for its impact on the family.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-09-24T10:14:17.8061286Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91502/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91502/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-09-10","Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 15 August 2011 calling for a family test to be applied to all domestic policy, which policies of her Department have been so assessed to date.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","208855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91503","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-10-13","<p>The temporary marquee positioned outside St Stephen’s Entrance is housing temporary search lanes while essential work is undertaken on the Cromwell Green Entrance search facilities. This work is scheduled to be completed by 19 October and the Cromwell Green Entrance will then reopen. The temporary marquee will be removed following a short period of commissioning and testing of the new facility before returning the exterior of St Stephen’s Entrance to its previous arrangement. It is anticipated that this period will be minimal.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-10-13T12:20:48.2680333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91503/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91503/answer",,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-09-10","Palace of Westminster","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, when is it intended that the front exterior of St Stephen's Entrance will be restored to its former state; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","208914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91504","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-13","<p>DFID leads the UK’s work to end extreme poverty internationally. It does not have a lead responsibility for domestic policies and has not made any assessments using the family test.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-10-13T14:58:55.5685289Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91504/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91504/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-09-10","Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 15 August 2011 calling for a family test to be applied to all domestic policy, which policies of her Department have been so assessed to date.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","208856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91505","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-13","<p>As part of its International Development Committee hearing commitments, DFID is in the process of preparing a departmental framework on disability inclusion. This will set out our clear commitment, approach and actions to strengthening disability in our policy, programme and international work. It will also include an explanation of how we will strengthen departmental capability on disability, how we will influence our partners to do more, and a timeframe for taking forward the activities outlined in our response to the IDC recommendations.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-10-13T14:50:32.3486879Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91505/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91505/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-09-10","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will require staff in her Department to report on (a) consultations with disabled people and their organisations, (b) measure to increase inclusion in bilateral aid projects and (c) measures to increase inclusion in funding agreements with partner organisations.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Mr David Blunkett","208973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91506","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>The number of cases transferred (sent) to the Crown Court for each magistrates' courts bench area (local justice area) in North Wales from 2009 to 2013 is provided in Table 1. These figures do not include appeal cases, which are instigated by the appellant.</p><p> </p><p>The number of cases dealt with (disposed) in the Crown Court in North Wales from 2009 to 2013 is provided in Table 2. It includes cases sent from the magistrates’ courts, along with appeals and breach cases initiated at the Crown Court.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","208995","2014-10-13T12:49:25.2881866Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91506/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91506/answer","208994-5 numbers of cases.xls","Numbers of cases in mags to crown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91506/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Crown Courts: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cases were transferred from magistrates' courts to Crown courts in each magistrates' courts bench area in North Wales in the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91507","Department for Education","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Department for Education collects data on the reasons for which children have been placed in secure children’s homes. There are three categories: those that have been detained or sentenced by the criminal courts; those placed in a criminal justice context and those placed on ‘welfare grounds’ under the Children Act 1989 (the Act). On 31 March 2014 there were 104 children placed in Secure Children’s Homes across England and Wales on welfare grounds. Within this latter category, we do not hold data that allows us to determine whether each child has been convicted of a crime.</p><p>Restricting the liberty of a child outside of the criminal justice context is a serious step. Section 25 of the Act sets out the criteria which must be considered before placing a young person in secure accommodation.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Mr Edward Timpson",,"2014-10-13T16:16:21.0372521Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91507/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91507/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2014-09-10","Young Offenders: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of children held in secure children's homes who have not been convicted of any crime in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","208979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91508","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>The UK is regarded as a world leader in its work to tackle forced marriage. The Prime Minister hosted the UK’s first Girl Summit in July 2014, to build on current efforts and rally a global movement to end early and forced marriage, and FGM in a generation. The UK Government made commitments to act domestically and internationally, including promises to improve the police response, increase support available to those affected, and strengthen community-led prevention. Our work to repatriate victims is a key element of our work to end forced marriage. <br><br>Before paying for the repatriation of a victim of forced marriage back to the UK, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office takes every step to ensure there are no other means of obtaining funds from relatives or friends who may be willing to transfer money or purchase a ticket back to the UK. Only in exceptional circumstances and after other means of obtaining the funds have been exhausted will a discretionary loan be made available, which must be repaid at a later date. <br><br>Where it has been demonstrated that all possible avenues of funding have been exhausted and there is a clear inability to enter into a loan agreement (normally due to a victim being underage or not having sufficient mental capacity to sign an agreement), the FCO can provide limited financial support. Since April 2013, the average cost of repatriation in these cases has been £744.00.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-13T14:14:26.7668812Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91508/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91508/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-10","Forced Marriage: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the average cost is of repatriating a victim of forced marriage stranded outside the UK; and who is responsible for paying that cost.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","208976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91509","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>The number of cases transferred (sent) to the Crown Court for each magistrates' courts bench area (local justice area) in North Wales from 2009 to 2013 is provided in Table 1. These figures do not include appeal cases, which are instigated by the appellant.</p><p> </p><p>The number of cases dealt with (disposed) in the Crown Court in North Wales from 2009 to 2013 is provided in Table 2. It includes cases sent from the magistrates’ courts, along with appeals and breach cases initiated at the Crown Court.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","208994","2014-10-13T12:49:25.4294121Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91509/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91509/answer","208994-5 numbers of cases.xls","Numbers of cases in mags to crown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91509/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Crown Courts: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cases were dealt with by Crown courts in North Wales in the last five years for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91510","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Forced Marriage Unit leads on the UK Government’s forced marriage policy, outreach and casework, operating both in the UK, where support is provided to any individual, and overseas, where consular assistance is provided to British nationals, including dual nationals. From 2010 – 2013, the Forced Marriage Unit provided advice or assistance related to a possible forced marriage in 5990 cases. To provide more information on the nature of the assistance provided in all these cases, including those which have involved repatriation, would involve a disproportionate cost.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2014-10-13T14:17:03.1652606Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91510/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91510/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-09-10","Forced Marriage: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many habitual British residents, British dual nationals and British nationals have been rescued by British consular staff from forced marriages abroad and repatriated to the UK since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","208977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91511","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-14","<p>In 2013/14 41%(1) percent of young people who had been sentenced to custody were not receiving any education, training or employment at the end of their licence period.</p><p> </p><p>Our Transforming Youth Custody programme is improving the prospects of effective resettlement of young people leaving custody. We are working closely with other Government Departments to provide young people with the opportunities they need, including through the Youth Engagement Fund which will help to close the attainment gap for disadvantaged 14-17 year olds, including those that have come into contact with the youth justice system.</p><br />(1) Information is extracted from YOTs’ electronic case management system and is taken from the last week of the custodial licence period. These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems, which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing and can be subject to change over time.","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-14T09:05:37.577426Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91511/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91511/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Young Offenders: Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of young offenders released in the last 12 months are not in education, employment or training.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","208978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91512","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p /> <p><strong>The prison will be a huge benefit to the region. Once operational it is estimated that the prison will create around 1,000 jobs and boost the local economy by around £23m per year. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Members of Parliament from North Wales have been kept informed at key project milestones or of issues of regional interest including site selection, identification of a preferred contractor and a local supplier event.</strong><strong> I will continue to ensure that Members are kept informed at future key milestones. </strong></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T12:23:04.4982799Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91512/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91512/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will take steps to keep local elected representatives informed of progress in the construction of a prison in North Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91513","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-14","<p><strong>Lend Lease have committed to employing at least 50% of the workforce locally to the prison and have committed to providing 100 apprenticeships throughout the contract. The MoJ will monitor this during the contract duration to ensure that these commitments are delivered.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Once operational, it is estimated that the prison will create around 1,000 jobs and boost the local economy by around £23m per year. </strong></p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-14T13:09:59.6259499Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91513/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91513/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the contract to build a prison in North Wales includes a requirement to (a) employ local workers and (b) employ and train apprentices.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91514","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>Whilst North Wales Police consulted on plans for their estate, including their property in Wrexham, in 2011, there has been no consultation between Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunal Service and other parties on the question of custody facilities at Wrexham Magistrates’ Court.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-13T16:26:47.4196307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91514/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91514/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Magistrates' Courts: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what consultation has taken place between his Department and interested parties on custody facilities at Wrexham Police Station currently used by Wrexham Magistrates' Court.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","209016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91515","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>Wrexham Magistrates’ Court has access to cells at Wrexham Police Station until late 2016 at the very least. HM Courts and Tribunals Service will make an assessment of all available options for custodial cases at Wrexham Magistrates’ Court thereafter.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-13T16:31:02.0692792Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91515/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91515/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Magistrates' Courts: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an assessment of the future availability of custody facilities at Wrexham Magistrates' Court in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","209017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91516","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p><strong>The Government has prioritised civil legal aid for the most important cases, including those involving wardship.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Under the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012, civil legal aid is available (subject to means and merits tests) for matters where the High Court exercises its inherent jurisdiction in relation to children and vulnerable adults.</strong></p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-13T10:26:40.6272687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91516/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91516/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Wardship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what legal aid his Department makes available for cases involving wardship.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","209037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91517","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>Following the Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice’s announcement on 15 July 2014 of the award of contracts to four companies to deliver the new electronic monitoring service, I am keen to work closely with Police and Crime Commissioners, police forces and other key stakeholders across the criminal justice system to ensure that opportunities to make use of the capability offered by the technology are fully exploited. We will be taking action over the coming months to engage with stakeholders.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","209059","2014-10-13T10:35:55.1170248Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91517/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91517/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2014, Official Report, column 398W, on electronic tagging, what progress he has made on involving police and crime commissioners in the stakeholder group for offender electronic monitoring technology; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","209058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91518","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-14","<p>The wardship jurisdiction is part of the inherent jurisdiction of the High Court. It is the duty of the court to ensure that a child who is the subject of proceedings is protected and taken care of. The wardship jurisdiction means the court has custody of the child who is a ward. No important step can be taken in the child's life without the court's consent.</p><p> </p><p>Data for the number of wardship applications made to courts in England and Wales during each of the last five calendar years is in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Applications for Wardship in England &amp; Wales</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Wardship Applications</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>396</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>267</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>428</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>452</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-14T15:18:23.6604174Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91518/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91518/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Wardship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many court cases involving wardship there were in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","209038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91519","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>Following the Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice’s announcement on 15 July 2014 of the award of contracts to four companies to deliver the new electronic monitoring service, I am keen to work closely with Police and Crime Commissioners, police forces and other key stakeholders across the criminal justice system to ensure that opportunities to make use of the capability offered by the technology are fully exploited. We will be taking action over the coming months to engage with stakeholders.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","209058","2014-10-13T10:35:55.194867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91519/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91519/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 13 January 2014, Official Report, column 398W, on electronic tagging, what progress he has made on engaging police forces as early adopters of the new arrangements for offender electronic monitoring technology; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","209059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91520","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p /> <p>The competition to select the providers of next-generation electronic monitoring services in England and Wales has now concluded.</p><p>On 15 July the Lord Chancellor and Secretary of State for Justice announced the award of contract to four companies who together will deliver the new Electronic Monitoring service. British company Steatite will develop and manufacture the equipment. Capita will manage the overall service, Airbus Defence and Space will provide satellite-mapping and Telefonica will supply the network.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T10:43:07.7334836Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91520/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91520/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to announce a new preferred bidder for the national contract for electronic offender-monitoring technology.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","209060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91521","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-27","<p>The table below sets out the amounts spent on electronic monitoring services provided by G4S and Serco for the years requested.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£116,906,087</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£107,684,810</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£36,987,915</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The 2013-14 figure is significantly lower as we withheld payment in 2013 once we became aware of long-standing anomalies in the billing arrangements on these contracts. We have since recovered all money owed on the contracts from the suppliers.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2014 Capita took over the management of the electronic monitoring service, on an interim basis until the new service comes into operation. Under these interim arrangements, G4S and Serco no longer have a direct role in delivering the service on the ground – and we have far greater oversight of costs and charging than previously, with direct access to the suppliers’ systems. We continue to manage these arrangements robustly.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-27T16:26:45.4136607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91521/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91521/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department spent on its contract for offender electronic monitoring in (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13 and (c) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","209057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91522","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>The contract with Capita to manage the existing electronic monitoring service on an interim basis, until the new service comes into operation, will cost a total of £67.1m up to December 2014.</p><p>Under these interim arrangements, G4S and Serco no longer have a direct role in delivering the service on the ground – and we have far greater oversight of costs and charging than previously, with direct access to the suppliers’ systems.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T12:18:33.3764283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91522/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91522/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the value is of the contract awarded to Capita for the continuation of electronic monitoring contracts on an interim basis.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","209061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91523","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>I have previously announced that we will begin using the new tags with satellite technology by the end of the year with offenders subject to release on temporary licence from prison. This will be initially on a limited basis as the new tags become available, and will allow us to undertake assurance testing prior to wider rollout.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T10:52:12.0650428Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91523/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91523/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 31 March 2014, to the hon. Member for Barnsley Central, Official Report, column 528W, on electronic tagging, whether the anticipated roll-out of satellite tagging by the end of the year will be on a full or pilot basis.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","209062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91524","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-14","<p>On 18 August 2014 the Prime Minister announced that the family test was being formalised as part of the impact assessment for all domestic policies. From October 2014, every new domestic policy will be examined for its impact on the family.</p>","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Simon Hughes",,"2014-10-14T15:10:28.1882634Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91524/answer","Biography information for Simon Hughes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91524/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 15 August 2011 calling for a family test to be applied to all domestic policy, which policies of his Department have been so assessed to date.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","208857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91525","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-21","<p>We are currently implementing major reforms to probation services in order to bring about a reduction in reoffending, with contracts to transfer ownership of the 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) on track to be signed by the end of 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The two main elements of the payment mechanism for CRCs are the Fee For Service (FFS) and Payment by Results (PbR). The FFS is primarily paid for mandated activities that deliver the sentence of the court and licence conditions. PbR is paid for the achievement of reductions in reoffending against the baseline historical level and is designed to incentivise bidders to continuously innovate and improve performance throughout the life of the contract.</p><p> </p><p>PbR measurement will be based on a series of offender “cohorts”. These are the groups of offenders whose reoffending will determine the providers’ success or otherwise at reducing reoffending rates. Cohorts will be built up on a quarterly and annual basis and will include offenders released from a custodial sentence and offenders who begin a community order (CO) or a suspended sentence order (SSO). Cohorts will exclude offenders not subject to any of the above disposals, and offenders allocated to the National Probation Service. They will also exclude offenders on a CO or SSO which includes only a single electronically monitored requirement (as CRCs will not be responsible for supervising this group) and offenders who are subject only to an unpaid work requirement (as for this group, the court will not have imposed an additional rehabilitative intervention).</p><p> </p><p>CRCs will be paid for reducing reoffending rates significantly beyond historic levels. Those historic baselines are modelled to exclude the same types of offender that are excluded in the CRCs’ cohorts, thereby allowing a like-for-like comparison.</p><p> </p><p>We have consulted widely on the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms and received and responded to a balance of views. The design of the payment mechanism has been set out in the draft payment mechanism design overview and draft payment mechanism contract schedule, copies of which were deposited in the Library of the House and published on the MoJ website in February 2014.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-21T12:46:49.7611674Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91525/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91525/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Offenders: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will place in the Library copies of all representations he has received on the consequences of excluding low risk offenders under community service orders from the payment by results model; and what estimate he has made of the potential effect of that conclusion on re-offending rates.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","208833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91526","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p>On 4 September 2014, the Secretary of State for Justice met the Chairman of the Parole Board, Sir David Calvert-Smith, and Claire Bassett, Chief Executive of the Parole Board.</p><p> </p><p>One of the issues that the meeting discussed was victim personal statements. It was agreed that victim personal statements play an important role in the parole process and can be used, by the panel, to assess whether the offender understands the full impact of their crimes on the victim.</p><p> </p><p>The meeting also noted that the independent Parole Board will prepare guidance to victims about the role of victim personal statements in the parole process.</p><p> </p><p>Victims of crime need and deserve the best possible support. It is right that victims of such horrific crimes are able to submit a Victim Personal Statement to the Parole Board considering the offender’s case, setting out how the offence has affected them and the impact that the offender’s release would have.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T12:21:03.269019Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91526/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91526/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Parole Board","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the contribution by the Minister for Policing, Criminal Justice and Victims of 9 September 2014, Official Report, column 748, on victims of crime, if he will publish the notes of his meeting with the Parole Board Group.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","208890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91527","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p><strong>Lend Lease were announced as the contractor for the design and build of the prison in North Wales on the 30<sup>th</sup> May 2014 and the Project Partnering Agreement contract was signed on the 15<sup>th</sup> July 2014.</strong></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T12:26:23.3140582Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91527/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91527/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he signed the contract with Lend Lease to construct a prison in North Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91528","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-15","<p>The decision as to who will operate the prison in North Wales has yet to be made. Once a provider has been identified it will be expected that their plans for operation will include the involvement of the voluntary sector and other providers to maximise rehabilitative opportunities for offenders.</p><p><br>Although a decision has not been made on the operator, discussions have taken place with PACT (Prisoner Advice and Care Trust), the voluntary sector umbrella group which focuses on the children and families of prisoners, to inform the design of visits areas and other aspects of the build which have implications for children and families.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-15T08:58:13.1673227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91528/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91528/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to engage with the voluntary sector in connection with the running of the new prison in North Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91529","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-13","<p /> <p><strong>MoJ is working with Lend Lease and local stakeholders to achieve the commitments made for the project, including providing 100 apprenticeships throughout the life of the project and 500 work placements per year. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>This includes the creation of a North Wales Prison Employment, Skills and Engagement Committee that is focusing on enabling the delivery of apprenticeships, training and local employment and work placement days.</strong></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-13T12:31:05.8792385Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91529/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91529/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to engage with training providers in North Wales in connection with the construction of the new prison in North Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91530","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-15","<p>Under the contractual arrangements in place, Lend Lease are required to report to the MoJ how much of the contract is being spent with companies within a 25 and 50 mile radius of the prison site. In addition Lend Lease has committed to spending £30 million with local businesses and that 50% of the entire workforce will be recruited from within a 50 mile radius. Lend Lease will report against these targets and the MoJ will monitor these accordingly.</p><p> </p><p>The North Wales Prison Employment, Skills and Engagement Committee is also being created to focus on enabling the delivery of apprenticeships, training and local employment and work placement days.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-15T16:05:07.9836516Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91530/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91530/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-09-10","Prisons: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how he plans to monitor and assess the benefit to North Wales of the construction of a prison in North Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian Lucas","208940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91531","Leader of the House","false","2014-09-23","<p>On 18 August 2014 the Prime Minister announced that the family test was being formalised as part of the impact assessment for all domestic policies. From October 2014, every new domestic policy will be examined for its impact on the family.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Mr William Hague",,"2014-09-23T14:13:08.1500911Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91531/answer","Biography information for Lord Hague of Richmond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91531/answer",,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2014-09-10","Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 15 August 2011 calling for a family test to be applied to all domestic policy, which policies of his Office have been so assessed to date.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","208858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91532","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-10-14","<p>On 18 August 2014, my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister announced that the family test was being formalised as part of the impact assessment for all domestic policies. From October 2014, every new domestic policy will be examined for its impact on the family.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-10-14T12:53:31.2376964Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91532/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91532/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-09-10","Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to the Prime Minister's speech of 15 August 2011 calling for a family test to be applied to all domestic policy, which policies of her Department have been so assessed to date.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","208859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91533","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>Applying the provisions of United Nations Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 1325 in respect of Northern Ireland is not appropriate as the situation has never been considered to be an armed conflict as defined in international law.</p><p>However, the Government considers some aspects of UNSCR 1325 relevant to Northern Ireland, including continuing to support the increase in the representation of women in Northern Ireland in public and political life in line with Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women (CEDAW) obligations.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-10-13T14:35:33.5319361Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91533/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91533/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-09-10","Special EU Programmes Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of how the Special EU Programmes Body is meeting its UNSCR 1325 and CEDAW obligations.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","208931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91534","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>Peace III is a unique and important programme that plays a valuable role in underpinning support for the devolution settlement in Northern Ireland. Responsibility for the Special EU Programmes Body is a devolved matter and the responsibility of Northern Ireland Executive Ministers.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","208930","2014-10-13T14:37:43.5295711Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91534/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91534/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-09-10","Special EU Programmes Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if she will assess how the Special EU Programmes Body has assisted in the promotion of women's involvement in PEACE 111 funding projects.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","208932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91535","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>Peace III is a unique and important programme that plays a valuable role in underpinning support for the devolution settlement in Northern Ireland. Responsibility for the Special EU Programmes Body is a devolved matter and the responsibility of Northern Ireland Executive Ministers.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","208932","2014-10-13T14:37:43.4502441Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91535/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91535/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-09-10","Special EU Programmes Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the performance of the Special EU Programmes Body in administering the PEACE 111 Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","208930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91536","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-16","<p>The creation of the Open Business Forum was announced on 23 February 2012 by my Rt. Hon. Friend the Prime Minister, who asked his adviser on corporate responsibility, Philip N. Green, to act as Chair. Companies and organisations represented on the Open Business Forum included Business in the Community, Trading for Good, Aviva, Procter and Gamble, Carillion, E.ON and Waitrose. As this Department did not provide the secretariat for this group, I am unable to confirm how many times the Open Business Forum met and whether it is planned that the minutes of its meetings will be made public.</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-16T15:27:52.783638Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91536/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91536/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-09-10","Open Business Forum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many times the Open Business Forum that he asked Sir Philip Green to set up in 2012 has met; and whether he plans that minutes of those meetings will be made public.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","209010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91537","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-13","<p>Neither HMG files nor information generally is classified under the Official Secrets Act; rather the Act creates an offence for the unauthorised disclosure of information that is defined as being damaging under it. All requests for information are considered under the provisions of the Freedom of Information Act.</p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude",,"2014-10-13T16:24:04.7508395Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91537/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91537/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-09-10","Official Secrets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether all requests for information on files covered by the Official Secrets Act 1989 receive a standard response or are considered on a case by case basis.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","208991"
