"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91540","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>We are unable to disaggregate the amount spent specifically on cycling from spend on consultancy. Furthermore, between 2005 and 2011 Cycling England were responsible for investment in cycling, however they were not consultants. For local highway authorities we do not keep this information centrally.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-13T13:33:06.0863885Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91540/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91540/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much (a) his Department and (b) local highways authorities have spent on consultants for cycling programmes, activities or projects in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","208874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91541","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department has received fourteen separate pieces of correspondence relating to metric mixers as at 24 September 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-13T12:26:56.5619446Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91541/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91541/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent representations he has received on the applicability of road safety regulations to metric mixers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","208875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91542","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-15","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>While the Government does not believe that the Proposal was necessary in respect of a proven competitive market based port sector, the Government has negotiated to secure an outcome that ensures the continued commercial integrity of our highly competitive port sector. I am pleased to say that the general approach agreed by the Transport Council on 8 October does represent a great improvement in this regard, as compared with the Commission’s original Proposal, and takes account of several key UK industry concerns.</p><p> </p><p>I have had – and continue to have – extensive and detailed discussions with not only the UK Major Ports Group and British Ports Association, but with trade unions and others who are likely to be affected by the Proposal; and I discussed the matter personally with the outgoing Commissioner, Siim Kallas, ahead of Transport Council.</p><p>The Government remains committed to addressing the very real concerns of industry, its employees, suppliers and customers, and to securing the best deal for our port sector and I will continue to challenge Brussels to recognise the circumstances of our unique ports sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-10-15T12:52:23.7986243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91542/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91542/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Ports: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the Government's policy is on the EU Port Services Regulations; and what discussions he has had on those regulations with the UK Major Ports Group.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","208865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91543","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Department has not provided secretarial support to the Norwich in 90 campaign but has been providing technical support within the Department’s staff resources. The Department has funded external consultancy support to the value of £60,000.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-13T11:21:56.0152313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91543/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91543/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","East Anglia Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the value is of the support provided by his Department to the Norwich in 90 campaign; and what proportion of such support has been spent on (a) secretarial support and (b) external consultants.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","208894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91544","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p>Directly Operated Railways (DOR) has incurred mobilisation costs in respect of two rail franchises since 6 May 2010. These are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2012/13 – InterCity West Coast - £1,020,000</p><p>2013/14 – Greater Western - £787,000</p><p> </p><p>Prior to 2010 DOR also incurred mobilisation costs of £5.6 million with respect to the failure of the InterCity East Coast franchise in 2009.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-13T16:47:51.7430904Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91544/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91544/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Directly Operated Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2014, Official Report, column 402W, on directly operated railways, what the mobilisation costs incurred by directly operated railways were in each franchise competition since 6 May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","208918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91545","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p>There are 89 level crossings of all types between London and Norwich. Network Rail are currently developing detailed proposals and costings to increase speeds on the route to reduce journey times and these proposals are likely to involve changes to some existing level crossings.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-13T11:23:24.772214Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91545/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91545/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","East Anglia Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many level crossings there are on the London to Norwich rail route; what assessment has been made of the number of level crossings that could be closed to improve passenger journey times; and what assessment has been made of the cost of closing level crossings as part of the Norwich in 90 proposals.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","208895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91546","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Department has not held direct discussions with the freight operating companies on this, as freight routeing is a matter for Network Rail, within the regulatory framework overseen by the Office of Rail Regulation. There are no current proposals to transfer all freight services from the Great Eastern Main Line to the Felixstowe to Nuneaton route; rather, the upgrading of the route from Felixstowe to Nuneaton is currently principally aimed at accommodating the anticipated growth in rail freight to and from the Port of Felixstowe.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-13T11:24:36.1322364Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91546/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91546/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","East Anglia Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has held with freight operating companies on the transfer of freight services from the Great Eastern Main Line to the Nuneaton to Felixstowe line.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","208896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91547","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Department has consulted with representatives of the European Tyre and Rim Technical Organisation, Michelin, Bandvulc Tyres, the British Tyre Manufacturers’ Association and the Retread Manufacturers Association.</p><p> </p><p>Further research is being planned but has not yet been commissioned. The outcomes will be available next year.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","208901","2014-10-13T11:26:21.9644386Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91547/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91547/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Buses: Tyres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which British and European tyre manufacturing experts have contributed to his Department's research into tyre ageing on buses and coaches since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","208900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91548","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-13","<p>The Department has consulted with representatives of the European Tyre and Rim Technical Organisation, Michelin, Bandvulc Tyres, the British Tyre Manufacturers’ Association and the Retread Manufacturers Association.</p><p> </p><p>Further research is being planned but has not yet been commissioned. The outcomes will be available next year.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","208900","2014-10-13T11:26:22.0641485Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91548/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91548/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Buses: Tyres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which individuals have been commissioned to undertake research into tyre ageing on buses and coaches; and when he will publish the results of such research.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","208901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91549","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-15","<p>Minor Highways Agency schemes are identified from the needs of the strategic road network. They are assessed on the basis that they will meet the need identified at the right time and that they are value for money. The number of Highways Agency minor schemes currently scheduled for delivery in 2014/15 is in excess of 4,000 and a similar number are under development for 2015/16 and future years. The information requested therefore could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-10-15T09:07:06.2658091Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91549/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91549/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Roads","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish the cost-benefit ratio of all current Highways Agency minor schemes under development and the applicable Transport Analysis Guidance (WebTAG) appraisal summary table for all such schemes.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","208884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91550","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-15","<p>The Department notes the recommendation that the relevant guidance on this subject should be updated.</p><p> </p><p>The Department expects to bring the successor to the Traffic Signs Regulations and General Directions, which will include all pedestrian crossing types, into force in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Pedestrian walking speeds and crossing timings are matters for guidance rather than legislation. The Department intends to produce a new chapter of the Traffic Signs Manual on traffic lights and pedestrian crossings, bringing together and updating existing advice. A timetable for publication has not yet been set.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-15T15:13:02.5024231Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91550/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91550/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Pedestrian Crossings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the report published by Living Streets and Transport Research Laboratory entitled, A Review of Pedestrian Walking Times and Time Needed to Cross the Road, if his Department will conduct an assessment of the road safety benefits to pedestrians of adjusting the time to cross at signalised crossings.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","208836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91551","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-14","<p>Historically Network Rail was classified to the private sector and borrowed from the markets. Government provided a financial indemnity in return for a fee from Network Rail to Government. The fee was set by the Office of the Rail Regulator to reflect the market cost of the indemnity. The financial indemnity allowed Network Rail to borrow using the strength of the Government’s balance sheet, whilst leaving it the normal private sector freedom to manage its own treasury policy.</p><p> </p><p>Following the Office of National Statistic’s announcement that Network Rail would be classified to the public sector from 1 September 2014, Network Rail’s borrowing and liquidity is being managed as part of central Exchequer processes.</p><p> </p><p>Department for Transport (DfT) is lending to Network Rail on terms consistent with the Regulator’s expectations of Network Rail’s cost of debt over control period 5. That is, the cost to Network Rail is intended to be broadly unchanged.</p><p> </p><p>Previously Network Rail paid a fee to Government for the financial indemnity and interest to the market, which could be thought of as the underlying government benchmark rate (i.e. gilts) plus a small premium. Network Rail now pays the equivalent amount to Government. In control period 5 (CP5: 2014-2019) we estimate a saving to the taxpayer of c.£95m to £190m on debt issuance of £28.5bn (now effectively gilt issuance), assuming that the premium to gilts would have been between 0.2% and 0.4%.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail estimates that the average premium paid over Gilts across control period 3 (CP3) and control period 4 (CP4) was 0.15% to 0.25%. Given the mix of funding and number of instruments issued over time we have not attempted to estimate the theoretical saving to taxpayers if Network Rail had borrowed from Government in CP3 and CP4 and the premium had been retained by the taxpayer. It is also not possible to quantify the potential impact on gilt rates had additional debt been source by the exchequer.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","208958 ; 208959 ; 208960 ; 208961","2014-10-14T11:45:35.1842481Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91551/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/91551/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-09-10","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what interest rate would have been charged if Network Rail had borrowed from the Government in each year of control periods 3, 4 and 5.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","208962"
